Draft of argument to build an academic paper around: Popper's Epistemology as the Correct Foundation for Science Education
Body = ~2669 words, endnotes = ~2581
Note that the citations in the endnotes need some work still.

In 1974, Richard Feynman stood before the graduating class at Caltech and apologized. He apologized on behalf of physics professors everywhere for never teaching students the scientific approach directly; for assuming they would absorb it by exposure to scientific work, the way islanders in the Pacific absorbed the forms of airport culture by watching planes land.1 Feynman was identifying a specific problem: the training pipeline for scientists does not explicitly teach the scientific approach, what Popper called epistemology¹, and as a result even honest, well-intentioned scientists end up practicing what Feynman called cargo cult science without realizing it, reproducing the surface forms of scientific inquiry without the epistemological substance that makes it genuine. But there is a second and related problem that compounds the first. K-12 teachers and education researchers who went through formal education programs encounter epistemology directly, but in a form that actively obscures rather than clarifies the foundation science education should rest on. Those programs treat Popper's epistemology as one voice among several equally valid options, giving teachers not an absent epistemological foundation but a confused one. Problem one produces scientists whose epistemological grounding, if they have it at all, was acquired through implicit modeling rather than explicit teaching, a weaker and less reliable mechanism that works for some but leaves most without the clear epistemological foundation that direct instruction would provide. Problem two produces teachers who teach content without epistemological grounding because they were taught that no single epistemological foundation is correct. Both problems produce the same outcome, students who never explicitly learn the scientific approach, but through different mechanisms requiring different solutions. Fifty years after Feynman's apology, neither problem has been adequately addressed. Both problems produce the same outcome, students who never explicitly learn the scientific approach, through different mechanisms. But both share the same broad recognition as their solution, and this paper treats them as one fundamental problem: that Popper's epistemology is not one voice among equals but the correct foundation for science education, and that treating it otherwise, whether through absence or through false equivalence, has specific and measurable consequences for how students learn to reason. The narrow solutions each problem requires in its specific context follow from that recognition and are addressed in subsequent work. 
The problem is visible in any survey of philosophy of education curricula. Epistemology sections routinely list Popper alongside Kuhn, Lakatos, Feyerabend, and others as if the question of how science works remains genuinely open; as if there is no better and worse answer, only different perspectives. This is a mistake physics education does not make. We do not teach Aristotelian physics alongside Einsteinian relativity as equally valid current options. We teach Aristotle as a historically important predecessor whose ideas were falsified and replaced by theories that have survived all attempts at refutation. Aristotelian mechanics was falsified and replaced by theories that have themselves since been falsified and replaced in turn. Some questions get settled in exactly this way, including epistemological ones, and treating settled questions as permanently open is not intellectual balance but intellectual paralysis. A teacher who has been taught that Popper is one interesting option among several has no clear epistemological framework when deciding how to teach scientific reasoning. They default to teaching content, because content is less controversial, while the epistemological process remains implicit and unexamined, exactly the situation Feynman was describing.
The apparent conflicts between Popper and his successors dissolve under scrutiny. Popper's epistemology has attracted extensive criticism from multiple directions, but the consistent pattern across that literature is that genuine contributions complement his core normative claim rather than defeat it, while apparent contradictions rest on mischaracterizations of his actual position.² His core normative claim is that knowledge requires falsifiability and survival of genuine attempts at refutation rather than justification by supporting evidence. Kuhn, for instance, argued that Popper attributed to science a linear, gradual convergence on final certain truth, and rejected this. But Popper never made that claim nor does his theory imply it. He prescribed a mechanism, bold conjecture exposed to rigorous criticism, not a pace or scale of change, and not convergence on a final destination. As Deutsch clarified, progress toward truth in Popper's framework means movement from more flawed theories to less flawed theories, a direction of travel, not an arrival point.³ The conflict dissolves once Popper's actual position is read rather than the position attributed to him. Education curricula that treat the post-Popperian debate as leaving the normative question permanently open are inheriting mischaracterizations of Popper's actual position rather than resolving them, and leaving teachers without the epistemological foundation they need.
What teaching Popper correctly would change in practice begins with understanding what Popper corrected. Aristotle's justificationism, the idea dominant in Western thought for two thousand years that knowledge requires justification by other knowledge, produces an infinite regress with no resolution.5 Popper's replacement: knowledge requires not justification but refutation.6 A claim counts as knowledge not because it has been proven true by supporting evidence but because it has survived all attempts to show it false. The difference becomes vivid through a concrete example. Consider a murder trial. The prosecution presents a theory that the defendant committed the crime, supported by empirical evidence consistent with that theory. But the defense attorney doesn't need to prove the prosecution wrong directly; they only need to present an alternative theory that is also consistent with the same empirical evidence. That alone is sufficient to destroy the prosecution's case, because it demonstrates that the evidence was never as decisive as it appeared. Confirmation is meaningless. If a theory is consistent with all the empirical evidence, that does not imply that it's correct. A teacher who genuinely understands this teaches students to ask not "what evidence supports my theory?" but "what evidence would distinguish my theory from competing ones?" and “what alternative theories would also explain all the evidence?” They teach students that an explanation consistent with everything explains nothing. They teach students to trace causal mechanisms rather than accumulate correlations, because a correlation consistent with multiple causal theories does not help you select a theory from its rivals.
Popperian falsificationism leads naturally to a further requirement that is implicit in his framework even though he didn't use this vocabulary explicitly. Science deals with systems, phenomena produced by causally interacting parts, and falsifying a causal claim requires first understanding which parts of the system are relevant and how they interact. To falsify a causal claim you must first identify what causal claim you are actually making, and that requires understanding how the parts of the system relate to each other causally. A correlation between two phenomena is consistent with multiple competing causal theories and therefore falsifies none of them. The correct question is not "does this observation fit my theory?" but "what is the causal mechanism connecting these parts of the system, and at what level does the root cause operate?" This is systems thinking; tracing causal relationships between the parts of a system to identify the constraint generating the problem at its deepest level rather than stopping at a surface correlation or a symptom. Goldratt made this vocabulary explicit, but the requirement is already implicit in Popper.⁷ You cannot do falsificationism correctly without doing systems thinking, because falsificationism requires identifying the causal mechanism you are actually testing, and identifying that mechanism requires understanding the system's causal structure at the level where the root cause operates.
The practical consequences are visible in oral examination of premed students using Socratic questioning.8 The most common reasoning failure encountered is not factual ignorance; students can reproduce correct answers. It is the inability to explain the causal mechanism one level below the emergent property being described. This is one illustration of a broader pattern; students trained without explicit epistemological grounding exhibit a range of reasoning failures that share the same root cause, of which the correlation-causation confusion discussed below is another example. Asked why oxygen moves from the lungs into the bloodstream, a student will say 'because of diffusion.' Asked to explain what diffusion is and why it happens, the same student will often say 'it's when molecules move from high concentration to low concentration', and consider the question answered. That second answer sounds like a real definition because it is correct. But it is a redescription of the observation, not an explanation of the mechanism that produces it. The word 'diffusion' sounds like an explanation because it is a technical term, and 'molecules move from high concentration to low concentration' sounds like a definition because it is accurate, but neither identifies the causal mechanism that generates the phenomenon. The actual mechanism, that molecules are in constant random motion, that the concentration gradient means more collisions occur in the direction of lower concentration, and that this asymmetry in collision frequency produces net directional movement, is precisely what both answers omit. A student who had been taught the difference between description and explanation would recognize that their answer was incomplete and would know what completing it requires. They have not been taught that explanation requires identifying the mechanism, not just restating the phenomenon at a slightly more abstract level or attaching a technical label to it. This is a direct consequence of science education that teaches conclusions without teaching the epistemological standard that distinguishes a genuine explanation from a redescription. A student who had been explicitly taught Popper's framework, that an explanation must identify a falsifiable causal mechanism, would know that their answer was incomplete and would know what completing it requires. The same failure appears in how many students handle correlation and causation. They know the phrase as a slogan. They do not reliably apply it as a reasoning tool, because they have never been taught the Popperian reason it matters; a correlation without a causal mechanism is an unfalsified just-so story, consistent with multiple competing theories and therefore does not help us select a theory from its rivals.
When students trained without explicit epistemological grounding become physicians, the same reasoning failures operate at an institutional scale with serious consequences. The organization of medicine into narrow specialties, gastroenterology, neurology, cardiology, endocrinology, is a structural systems thinking failure embedded in the profession itself. Many specialists look at their part of the system without asking what the root cause is at the level of the whole patient. A gastroenterologist treats gut symptoms, a neurologist treats cognitive symptoms, an endocrinologist treats hormonal symptoms, each within their own theoretical framework, each limited to the hypotheses their specialty generates, none necessarily asking what constraint is operating at the level of the whole biological system and producing manifestations across multiple domains simultaneously. The patient is fragmented into organs that are treated independently when the root cause may be operating at the interface between what two specialists consider their separate territories. Medicine's own internal correction of this failure is revealing; when the silo structure produces bad enough outcomes, a bridging specialty gets created. Interventional neurology emerged because the boundary between neurology and vascular medicine was producing worse stroke outcomes than a specialty that explicitly traced root causes across that boundary. Neuropsychiatry emerged because the boundary between neurology and psychiatry was preventing the identification of neurological root causes of psychiatric symptoms. Each bridging specialty is medicine recognizing, after the fact, that the institutional structure was artificially separating things that are causally connected in the actual biological system. The physicians exposing these failures are doing exactly what Popperian training should produce; tracing causal relationships across the whole system, refusing to treat symptoms while ignoring what generates them, and proposing bolder hypotheses about root causes that the existing institutional framework wasn't generating. Their relative rarity is the problem.9 Their existence is the proof that systems thinking in medicine produces better outcomes when it is finally applied.
The analysis in this paper establishes that the Scientific Approach needs to be taught explicitly rather than assumed to be absorbed by osmosis, and that this requires deliberate curricular attention at multiple levels of education. What explicit instruction in the Scientific Approach should look like in practice, how it should be sequenced within existing degree programs, what it should contain at introductory versus advanced levels, what teacher training it requires, and how its outcomes should be measured, are questions that demand educational research expertise beyond the scope of this epistemological argument. A full account of what the Scientific Approach as a teachable framework consists of at the level of its domain-general principles, is beyond the scope of this paper and is the necessary subject of subsequent work, recognizing that each discipline will develop its own domain-specific sub-methods in response to its particular challenges, as medicine developed the double blind experiment to address confounds that don't arise in the same form in other fields. That account must also address what structural proposals alone cannot, that a teacher without kindness and charisma will fail to reach students regardless of epistemological grounding, and that kindness and rationality are not separate virtues but structurally connected aspects of the same thing, each requiring the other to function correctly.10 Equally, a teacher without the social awareness to meet students where they are, explain ideas simply, and sustain genuine engagement through the discomfort of Socratic examination will fail to deliver the framework effectively regardless of how well they understand it.11
The epistemological confusion this paper identifies is not a minor academic oversight; it has consequences that reach from philosophy seminars all the way into the clinic, where physicians trained without explicit epistemological grounding make reasoning errors that cost patients their lives. A teacher who has been taught that Popper is one voice among equals cannot confidently teach Popperian reasoning as the correct foundation for scientific thinking. A professor who doesn't clearly understand the difference between falsificationism and justificationism cannot make that difference explicit in the first two weeks of their introductory course. Resolving that confusion requires education curricula to make a distinction they currently avoid, between epistemological questions that remain genuinely open and those that have been falsified and replaced by better frameworks. Popper's core insights belong in the second category. Treating them as belonging in the first has real costs, measured not in philosophical imprecision but in patient outcomes, in students who cannot distinguish explanation from redescription, and in entire subfields of science that spend decades accumulating confirming evidence for theories whose root causes they never correctly identified. That neither problem has been adequately addressed in the fifty years since Feynman's apology demands a deeper explanation than mere oversight. The deliberate design choices embedded in compulsory education systems, and their consequences for what gets taught and what gets systematically excluded, are documented by Gatto,12 a thirty-year New York City public school teacher and two-time recipient of both the New York City and New York State Teacher of the Year awards, and are addressed further in subsequent work. Getting this right is not an academic housekeeping matter. It is the most fundamental lever available for improving how the next generation of scientists, physicians, and thinkers actually reason, and it begins with taking seriously what Feynman was asking for fifty years ago.
